<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-04-08T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-04-08T12:00:00-05:00" n="267" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d267">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">862t.01/69a: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Wallace</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-04-08T13:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">April 8,
                                            1920—1 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                            <p>713. Cable promptly and fully for our guidance your impressions of
                                situation arising out of the Ruhr Valley question, particularly the
                                situation arising from occupation by French forces of Frankfort and
                                other cities. Also cable any information you can obtain or have
                                received in regard to actions which are contemplated by other
                                nations or communications which have been exchanged.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Colby</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>